At 3:38pm EDT Wednesday, Steven Hawley released the Hubble Space Telescope from   shuttle Discovery's mechanical arm.
Starboard solar wing unfurling took three tries and  caused a delay.
The 12-ton Hubble drifted into its orbit 380 miles above Earth.
Hubble's  94.5-inch mirror is to be exposed to starlight Friday, after Hubble's maneuverability is  tested to ensure the mirror can stay pointed away from the sun.
Discovery is following  Hubble so spacewalkers Bruce McCandless and Kathryn Sullivan can assist if the 10-foot  aperture door doesn't open properly.
Hubble's first transmitted image, of a star cluster in  constellation Carina, is expected Tuesday.
Technical delays and the Challenger explosion  delayed Hubble's launch since 1983. 
